Nvidia Corporation was founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem in Santa Clara, California. Initially focused on the emerging market for graphics processing units (GPUs), Nvidia launched its first product, the NV1, in 1995. Though it met limited success, the company made a major breakthrough in 1999 with the introduction of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first GPU. This innovation established Nvidia as a leader in computer graphics.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia continued its dominance with the GeForce series and expanded into the professional visualization and high-performance computing markets through its Quadro and Tesla product lines. In 2006, Nvidia released the CUDA programming platform, enabling developers to use GPU computing for general-purpose applications — a turning point for AI and scientific computing.

In the 2010s, Nvidia’s GPUs became central to the rise of artificial intelligence, deep learning, and autonomous driving technologies. Their hardware powered data centers, AI research, and self-driving vehicle platforms such as Nvidia Drive.

Nvidia also entered the gaming market more broadly with products like the Shield line and the launch of cloud gaming service GeForce Now. In 2020, Nvidia announced its intent to acquire ARM Holdings, a deal later abandoned following regulatory pressure.

Today, Nvidia is a key player in AI, gaming, and data center technologies, with its GPU architecture (including the RTX series and Hopper platform) widely adopted across industries. Under CEO Jensen Huang, Nvidia has grown into one of the world’s most valuable technology companies.

claude
______

# Nvidia: A Brief History

Founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, Nvidia began with a vision to revolutionize computer graphics. The company's name, combining "NV" (next version) with "invidia" (Latin for envy), reflected its ambitious goals.

In 1995, Nvidia released its first breakthrough product, the NV1 graphics card. However, it was the 1999 release of the GeForce 256—marketed as the world's first "GPU" (Graphics Processing Unit)—that truly established Nvidia as an industry leader.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia dominated the high-performance graphics market with its GeForce series for consumers and Quadro line for professionals. In 2006, the company introduced CUDA, a parallel computing platform that allowed developers to use GPUs for general-purpose computing beyond graphics.

This pivot proved visionary when the AI revolution began gaining momentum in the 2010s. Nvidia's GPUs became the preferred hardware for training deep learning models, dramatically expanding the company's market beyond gaming.

In 2016, Nvidia released the Tesla P100, specifically designed for AI data centers, followed by increasingly powerful architectures including Volta, Turing, Ampere, and Hopper.

By the 2020s, Nvidia had transformed from a graphics card manufacturer to a full-stack computing company powering everything from gaming to autonomous vehicles, cloud computing, and generative AI.

Under Huang's continuous leadership, Nvidia has grown from a startup to one of the world's most valuable companies, fundamentally reshaping modern computing.

